==English==
===Etymology===
From Old English '''rad''' (riding, hostile incursion) > Proto-Germanic '''[[*ridanan]]''' (to ride) >  from Proto-Indo-European '''[[*reidh-]]''' (to ride).

=== Pronunciation ===
*rōd, /rəʊd/, /<tt>r@Ud</tt>/
*:'''Homophones''': [[rode]], [[rowed]]
*:[[Rhymes:English:-əʊd|Rhymes: -əʊd]]

=== Noun ===
:A [[narrow]] strip of [[land]] made suitable for [[travel]] between [[places]]. Modern roads are usually paved to accommodate wheeled [[vehicle]]s.

===Prepositions===
The term road is used with the preposition on. Something is on the road, but in the street.

